  "sections": [
    {
      "hash": "cdc3d34e965f00cd71973ad3c6cdfaaa868585cc",
      "heading": "Zinc CNC Machining",
      "level": "h1",
      "text": "Capabilities Custom Online CNC Machining Services Zinc CNC Machining Zinc CNC Machining Get instant quotes on custom zinc machined parts with our Online CNC Machining Service. Make quick-turn prototypes and production parts in days with free standard shipping on all US orders. ISO 9001:2015, ISO 13485, IATF 16949:2016, and AS9100D certified. ITAR registered. Get Your Zinc CNC Machining Instant Quote"
    },
    {
      "hash": "0a10475d1a86e5525d103f876d76db1b7149346a",
      "heading": "Zamak 3 (Zinc alloy 3)",
      "level": "h2",
      "text": "Zamak 3 (Zinc alloy 3) The Zamak 3 alloy contains 4% aluminum while less than 1% is composed of copper and magnesium. Zamak Zinc alloys exhibit similar machinability to copper but are less abrasive to tooling. Automotive part shells and small electric motor casings are typical applications for this type of zinc."
    },
    {
      "hash": "6a16962310bc0b1681f058801f3345e9558e8a42",
      "heading": "Finshes and Post-Processing Options",
      "level": "h3",
      "text": "Finshes and Post-Processing Options Zinc alloys respond well to a wide range of surface finishes. Some of the more common finishes for CNC machined zinc are listed below: Chrome Plating: Zinc alloys are ideal materials for cosmetic applications due to their low price points. They are easy to chrome-plate in order to create parts with the feel and look of polished stainless steel at a fraction of the cost. Chromate conversion coating: Not to be confused with chrome plating, this process involves placing the zinc part in a chemical bath that will react with its surface. This reaction results in a part that is resistant to light chemical attacks. Different chromate compounds offer differing le..."
    },
    {
      "hash": "dfa106fdfdac1166838567f2e6ec2d7876f4d230",
      "heading": "Cost-saving Design Tips",
      "level": "h3",
      "text": "Cost-saving Design Tips Zinc is a cheap material, so at least some cost savings are built-in. However, to further leverage these savings, refer to the tips below.Â Casting: Depending on the volume of components required, expenses may be reduced by casting the part and then only machining critical dimensions and features into it. Non-critical parts : Zinc is ideal in applications where plastics wonât suffice but cost still needs to be kept to a minimum. Zinc alloys eliminate the need for advanced plastics and offer better long-term dimensional stability."
    },
